    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-07-17T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-07-17T15:00:00-05:00" n="905"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d905">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">894.6363/202a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-07-17T16:00:00-04:00"
                            >July 17, 1935—4 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>110. Your 151, July 16, 4 p.m.,<note n="18" xml:id="d905fn18">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_314">p. 314</ref>.</note> last
                    paragraph, and Department’s 109, July 16, 8 p.m.<note n="19" xml:id="d905fn19">
                        <hi rend="italic">Post</hi>, <ref target="#pg_981">p. 981</ref>.</note> As
                    Standard-Vacuum has indicated to Department continued concern with regard to
                    carrying out by Japanese authorities of assurances given orally in reference to
                    petroleum regulation in Japan, Department suggests that in your discretion you
                    mention this subject in the course of your final talk with the Foreign
                    Minister.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Phillips</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
